data.name: eA1R_text.Text
data.value: Around the year 800 AD the Vikings began to travel from homes in the countries we call Scandinavia – Norway,Sweden and Denmark. The Vikings were farmers. When the farmer died the farm was passed onto the eldest sonof the family. The Vikings had a lot of children! The younger children did not want to stay and work on their brother’s farm. So they decided to go over the seas to find new land and get rich. They travelled to many places, but they were often very cruel to the people they met. They burned towns and villages and stole people's land. The Vikings who lived in Norway went to England, Ireland and Scotland. But some others went much further. They moved to Iceland, Greenland and even America. Many towns in these places today still have Viking names. The Vikings needed good ships to make these sea journey. They built their longships, which are still famous today. Longships were ships of war and they were very fast. They were about 25 metres long, but the longest one ever found was 35 metres long. The largest ships carried more than sixty fighting men.

data.name: eA2R_text.Text
data.value: People believe that bungee jumping is a modern extreme sport, but, in reality, it comes from the island of Pentecost in the South Pacific, where young people jump off tall buildings with their feet tired with vinesto prove that they are brave.Bungee jumping is very popular all over the world and there are a lot of safetyregulations forthis sport. When you jump, the cord on your feet stretches and keeps you moving up and down very fast. Then, you start slowing down.You can see Bungee jumps in many films. Perhaps the most famous is the opening scene of the James Bond film GoldenEye , in which Bond makes a jump over a dam in Russia. Actually,the dam is the Verzasca Dam in Switzerland. This is a real jump , not a special effect.

data.name: label104.Text
data.value: A Healthy lifestyle is one a happy lifestyle. The good news is that there is no real secret about how to get that lifestyle.A few simple changes to our everyday life are all that is needed. Here are a few ideas to think about: -Be active. Research has shown that a little bit of exercise regularly is very important and reduced the changes of serious illness. We don’t have to run a marathon or spend hours in a gym. A walk in the park with friends ,a game of basketball or just cycling to work will all help. The trick is to do some exercise three or four times a week -Eat well. We all know that junk food is bad for us ,but we all eat it. Fewer sweets and crisps and more fresh fruit and vegetables will give us more energy and save us money. Fizzy drinks contain sugar and other chemicals that are bad for us. We should drink at least 8 glasses of water a day. It’s pure, healthy and comes from the tap. -Get out of house One of the worst things we do is sit at houme in front of the TV. Try to go out more and meet friends and relatives. We need to share our problems and realise that we are not alone in the world. We often keep our worries to ourselves and just talking to a friend can solve these worries or make them seem less important. None of us are perfect and we would all benefit from a healthier lifestyle. The changes we need to make are small. Get started now!

data.value: Imagine England hundreds of years ago, without a king young man named Arthur pulled a magic sword, ’Excalibur’ from a stone. data.name: label120.Text
data.value: Sun, sea and a stretch of sand are what makes a perfect holiday. Relaxing on the beach is the ultimate holiday experience for many people but do you know where beaches come from? You usually find beaches where the sea meets the coast. Beaches take thousands of years to form. The sea and the wind help make beaches. As waves crash onto rocky shores, they throw the rocks around and break them into stones and then into pebbles. With time, the waves grind the pebbles into sand. There are many different types of beaches. Each beach has its own characteristics that make it unique. They are beaches with black or green sand, which comes from lava from volcanoes. Other have pink or white sand which comes from coral. They are also beaches with shells, rocky beaches and ones covered with pebbles. Finally, they are beaches with beautiful sand hills called dunes which remind us of deserts.

data.value: a) The Universe is born 100 million years ago. b) At the beginning, the Universe was cold. c) Big groups of stars form galaxies. d) The Universe stopped expanding a long time ago. e) There is very big number of stars in the Universe today.

data.name: B1M1text2.Text
data.value: About 100 million years after the Big Bang, the gas become hot and dense enough for the first stars to form. They were born incredibly fast large groups of stars soon made up the first galaxies. They have various shapes but the most common are spiral, elliptical and irregular. Our galaxy is called the Milky Way. It is a giant spiral galaxy. Today we know that the Milky Way contain more than 100 billion stars and that they are some 100 billion galaxies in the Universe, each containing these enormous number of stars.

data.name: B1M1text.Text
data.value: Let’s go back in time about 13.7 billion years. The entire Universe is inside a bubble which is thousands of times smaller than a pinhead. It is hotter and denser than anything we can imagine. Then, it suddenly explodes. The Universe as we know it today, is born. Time, space and matter begin with the Big Bang. In less than a second, the Universe grows from smaller than a single atom to bigger than a galaxy. It cools down and it keeps growing at a fantastic speed. It is still expanding today.

data.name: B1M2Gtext2.Text
data.value: The British Airways London Eye is the world’s tallest observation wheel. It is 135 m high and takes 30 minutes to complete one full circle. The wheel is located on the banks of the River Thames and offers the best panoramic views over and around London. On a clear day, you can see a distance of 40 km in every direction. The wheel can carry 800 passengers each time around, which is equal to 11 full red double-decker buses! Each year over 3.5 million people from all over the world ride the London Eye.

data.name: B2M1RText.Text
data.value: The most well-known and trusted of British TV cooks, Delia Smith has been teaching the nation how to make its favourite dishes for over 30 years now. She’s often referred to as Britain’s queen of home cooking. Delia left school at 16 without any qualifications but it was the job she found at the tiny restaurant The Singing Chef in Paddington which sparked her passion for preparing food. Determined to study every aspect of English cookery, she worked through countless cookery books, many in the Reading Room at the British Museum. In 1969 Delia became the cookery writer for the Daily Mirror's new magazine, and three years later began columns for the Evening Standard and the Radio Times. Her TV career began in 1973 with BBC series Family Fare and was followed by Delia's Cookery Course with its back-to-basics recipes, also available in print. Delia Smith's Summer Collection and her Winter Collection followed and, in 1998, the How to Cook series was broadcasted, the accompanying book being her most successful yet. The BBC has recently shown a series called Delia Through the Decades, which celebrates the five decades of her career. Delia’s other great passion is football and in November 1996 she became Director of Norwich City FC.

data.name: B2M2RText.Text
data.value: An unemployed 48-year-old man from Osaka was arrested in September last year for stealing cash and valuables worth 19 million yen (about $185,000) from 32 different homes. His motive? To be able to afford premium cat food for his feline friends – more than 120, mostly stray cats but also about 20 of his own, living in a nearby warehouse. “It’s like the story of Jean Valjean in Les Miserables, only you have to replace Jean Valjean’s sister’s starving children with street cats and a loaf of bread with precious stones,” a Japanese police officer told the press. Unemployed Demizu gave his 120 feline friends fresh fish and chicken, not cheap canned food. “He said he felt happiest when he rubbed his cheek against the cats,” the officer added. It cost $250 a day to keep this kitty buffet open and running. So after he lost his job in 2011 and his own savings came to an end, Demizu had to embrace a life of crime in order to provide for the cats. He broke into houses in his neighborhood during the daytime when families were most likely to be at work or school. He entered through unlocked windows or by finding hidden keys outside of the homes. When he was caught by the police, Demizu pled guilty as charged, so that he could ask for mercy for his feline friends.
